NOTES_EPHESIANS = {
    1: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Apostolos" (ἀπόστολος, Strong\'s G652) denotes one sent with delegated authority, not merely a messenger. The phrase "en Ephesō" appears in brackets because several early manuscripts (P46, Sinaiticus, Vaticanus) omit the location, suggesting this may have been a circular letter. HISTORICAL: This has led many scholars to view Ephesians as an encyclical epistle intended for multiple churches in the province of Asia.',
        3: 'GREEK: "Eulogētos" (εὐλογητός, G2128) is a verbal adjective meaning "worthy of praise/blessing," used exclusively of God in the NT. The threefold occurrence of the eulog- root (eulogētos, eulogēsas, eulogia) creates a powerful wordplay: "Blessed be the one who blessed us with every blessing." STRUCTURE: Verses 3-14 form one continuous sentence in the Greek, the longest in the NT, functioning as a grand berakah (Jewish blessing formula). TYPOLOGY: The phrase "en tois epouraniois" (in the heavenly places) appears five times in Ephesians alone, establishing the cosmic scope of God\'s redemptive work.',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Exelexato" (ἐξελέξατο, G1586) is aorist middle voice — He chose for Himself — emphasizing divine initiative before creation. "Pro katabolēs kosmou" (before the foundation of the world) places election in eternity past, prior to any human action. GREEK: "Katabolē" (G2602) literally means "a casting down" or "a laying of a foundation," used of the founding act of creation itself (Heb 4:3, Matt 13:35). "Amōmos" (G299, blameless/without blemish) is sacrificial language drawn from the LXX requirement for unblemished offerings (Lev 1:3, 3:1).',
        5: 'GREEK: "Proorisas" (προορίσας, G4309) means "having marked out beforehand" or "having set boundaries in advance," from pro (before) + horizō (to determine/set a boundary). "Huiothesia" (υἱοθεσία, G5206) is a legal term from Roman adoption law by which the adopted son received the full rights and inheritance of a natural-born son. HISTORICAL: Under Roman law, adoption was irrevocable and the adopted son\'s former debts were cancelled — a powerful metaphor for the believer\'s new legal standing.',
        6: 'GREEK: "Echaritōsen" (ἐχαρίτωσεν, G5487) is a rare verb appearing only here and in Luke 1:28 (to Mary). It means "to bestow grace upon" or "to endue with grace" — literally "He graced us." TYPOLOGY: "The Beloved" (ho ēgapēmenos) echoes the Father\'s declaration at Christ\'s baptism (Matt 3:17) and transfiguration (Matt 17:5), and recalls Isaac as the beloved son of Abraham (Gen 22:2 LXX), the one through whom the inheritance comes.',
        7: 'GREEK: "Apolytrōsis" (ἀπολύτρωσις, G629) denotes a release effected by the payment of a ransom price, drawn from the slave-market. "Paraptōma" (G3900, trespass) literally means "a falling beside" or "a stepping aside," implying deviation from the path of righteousness. THEOLOGICAL: Redemption is explicitly grounded in Christ\'s blood — the cross as the ransom price — not in moral improvement or ritual observance. This echoes the Passover lamb typology (Exod 12:13) and the Day of Atonement blood rites (Lev 16:15-16).',
        10: 'GREEK: "Anakephalaiōsasthai" (ἀνακεφαλαιώσασθαι, G346) is a remarkable compound verb meaning "to sum up under one head" or "to recapitulate all things under a single heading." It appears in the NT only here and in Rom 13:9. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The scope of this reunification explicitly includes "the things upon the heavens" — the heavenly realm of spiritual powers — and "the things upon the earth," indicating Christ\'s kingship restores order to both the divine council realm and the human realm, reversing the fracturing described in the Deuteronomy 32 worldview (Deut 32:8-9 LXX). THEOLOGICAL: "Oikonomia" (G3622) denotes a household administration or stewardship, here referring to God\'s cosmic plan executed at the appointed time.',
        13: 'GREEK: "Esphragisthēte" (ἐσφραγίσθητε, G4972) means "you were sealed," an aorist passive indicative. A seal (sphragis) in the ancient world marked ownership, authenticity, and protection. THEOLOGICAL: The Holy Spirit Himself functions as the seal — not a separate act from the Spirit, but the Spirit\'s indwelling presence is the seal. "The Spirit of promise" (to pneuma tēs epangelias) is the Spirit who was promised in the OT prophets (Joel 2:28-29; Ezek 36:26-27; Isa 44:3), marking the new covenant age.',
        14: 'GREEK: "Arrabōn" (ἀρραβών, G728) is a Semitic loanword (Hebrew \'erabon, Gen 38:17-18) denoting a down payment or pledge guaranteeing the full amount to follow. THEOLOGICAL: The Spirit is not merely a symbol of future inheritance but a present installment of the glory to come — the same substance, given in part now, to be received in full at the "redemption of the possession" (apolytrōsis tēs peripoiēseōs), referring to the final bodily resurrection and cosmic restoration (Rom 8:23).',
        17: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The God of our Lord Jesus Christ" preserves the full divine-human reality of the incarnation — even the exalted Christ relates to the Father as His God (John 20:17). "The Father of glory" echoes the Shekinah tradition: God is the source and possessor of all divine radiance. GREEK: "Epignōsis" (ἐπίγνωσις, G1922) is an intensified form of gnōsis (knowledge), denoting full, experiential, relational knowledge rather than mere intellectual apprehension. "Apokalypsis" (G602) means an unveiling — spiritual sight is a gift, not a human achievement.',
        20: 'TYPOLOGY: The resurrection and enthronement of Christ at God\'s right hand fulfills Psalm 110:1 (LXX 109:1), the most quoted OT passage in the NT: "Sit at my right hand." Christ\'s exaltation follows the pattern of the Davidic king\'s enthronement but surpasses it infinitely in scope. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The seating "in the heavenly places" (en tois epouraniois) places Christ on the divine council throne itself, at the right hand of the Most High — the position of supreme executive authority over all spiritual beings.',
        21: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The four terms — "archē" (rule/principality, G746), "exousia" (authority, G1849), "dynamis" (power, G1411), and "kyriotēs" (dominion/lordship, G2963) — represent classes of spiritual beings in the heavenly hierarchy. Christ is enthroned "hyperanō" (far above) every rank of celestial power, both in the present age and the age to come. THEOLOGICAL: "Every name being named" encompasses all spiritual authorities, whether loyal to God or rebellious — none stands outside Christ\'s supreme sovereignty (Phil 2:9-11).',
        22: 'TYPOLOGY: "He subjected all things under His feet" directly quotes Psalm 8:6 (LXX), which describes the dominion originally given to Adam. Christ as the last Adam (1 Cor 15:27, 45) fulfills the mandate of Genesis 1:26-28 that the first Adam forfeited. GREEK: "Kephalē" (κεφαλή, G2776) meaning "head" carries the dual sense of authority/rule and source/origin. Christ is given as head "hyper panta" (over all things) to the assembly — His headship over creation is exercised for the benefit of His people.',
        23: 'GREEK: "Plērōma" (πλήρωμα, G4138) means "fullness" or "that which fills up." The church as Christ\'s body is the fullness of Christ, who Himself fills all things in all. THEOLOGICAL: The closing phrase "tou ta panta en pasin plēroumenou" can be read as middle voice ("the one filling all in all") rather than passive ("being filled"), affirming Christ\'s active, sovereign filling of all creation with His presence and rule. The church is thus the visible, corporate manifestation of Christ\'s cosmic lordship — His body through which He exercises His reign in the present age.',
    },
    2: {
        2: 'GREEK: "αἰῶνα τοῦ κόσμου τούτου" (aiōna tou kosmou toutou) literally "the age of this world"—a double expression combining temporal (age/era) and spatial (world-system) dimensions of the present evil order. DIVINE_COUNCIL: "τὸν ἄρχοντα τῆς ἐξουσίας τοῦ ἀέρος" (ton archonta tēs exousias tou aeros) — "the ruler of the authority of the air" identifies Satan as a cosmic potentate governing the spiritual domain between heaven and earth. In Second Temple Jewish cosmology, the "air" was understood as the realm inhabited by hostile spiritual powers (cf. Testament of Benjamin 3:4; Eph 6:12). The genitive chain identifies this ruler as operating through a spirit of disobedience that energizes (ἐνεργοῦντος, energountos) rebellious humanity.',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL: Paul shifts from "you" (Gentiles) to "we all" (including Jews), establishing universal condemnation under sin. "τέκνα φύσει ὀργῆς" (tekna physei orgēs) — "children by nature of wrath" — indicates that the condition of being under divine wrath is not merely behavioral but inherent to fallen human nature. This is a foundational text for the doctrine of original sin. GREEK: "ἀνεστράφημεν" (anestraphēmen, Strong\'s G390) means "conducted ourselves" or "lived among," carrying a sense of habitual manner of life.',
        5: 'GREEK: "συνεζωοποίησεν" (synezōopoiēsen, Strong\'s G4806) — "made alive together with" — is a compound verb with the prefix σύν (syn, "together with"), emphasizing the believer\'s union with Christ in His resurrection life. The parenthetical "χάριτί ἐστε σεσῳσμένοι" (chariti este sesōsmenoi) uses a periphrastic perfect: "by grace you are having been saved" — the perfect tense indicating a completed past action with continuing present results. TYPOLOGY: As God breathed life into Adam (Gen 2:7), so He makes dead sinners alive in the second Adam, Christ (1 Cor 15:22, 45).',
        6: 'THEOLOGICAL: Three σύν- (syn-) compound verbs span vv.5-6: made alive together with, raised together, seated together — each binding believers to Christ\'s resurrection, ascension, and heavenly enthronement. DIVINE_COUNCIL: "ἐν τοῖς ἐπουρανίοις" (en tois epouraniois) — "in the heavenly places" — the same realm where spiritual powers operate (Eph 1:20-21; 3:10; 6:12). Believers are positionally enthroned with Christ above the hostile spiritual authorities mentioned in v.2.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse is the locus classicus for the Protestant doctrine of sola gratia and sola fide. Grace (χάρις, charis) is the instrumental cause; faith (πίστις, pistis) is the means. "Τοῦτο" (touto, neuter "this") does not agree grammatically with either "grace" (feminine) or "faith" (feminine), indicating that the entire arrangement of salvation-by-grace-through-faith is "the gift of God." GREEK: The periphrastic perfect "ἐστε σεσῳσμένοι" (este sesōsmenoi) emphasizes the abiding state of having been saved — completed yet enduring.',
        10: 'GREEK: "ποίημα" (poiēma, Strong\'s G4161) — "workmanship" or "thing made" — from ποιέω (poieō, "to make"). English "poem" derives from this word. It emphasizes that believers are God\'s crafted work of art, not self-made. THEOLOGICAL: The verse resolves the tension between vv.8-9 and the role of works: good works are not the ground of salvation but its designed purpose. "προητοίμασεν" (proētoimasen) — "prepared beforehand" — indicates divine foreordination of the believer\'s path of obedience (cf. Eph 1:4-5, 11).',
        12: 'THEOLOGICAL: Five dimensions of Gentile alienation are enumerated: (1) apart from Christ, (2) alienated from Israel\'s commonwealth, (3) strangers to the covenants, (4) without hope, (5) without God (ἄθεοι, atheoi — the only NT occurrence of this word). HISTORICAL: "πολιτείας τοῦ Ἰσραήλ" (politeias tou Israēl) — "commonwealth of Israel" — uses a term from Greco-Roman civic life, conveying that Israel was a divinely constituted polity with covenant membership, from which Gentiles were excluded.',
        14: 'GREEK: "τὸ μεσότοιχον τοῦ φραγμοῦ" (to mesotoichon tou phragmou) — "the middle wall of the partition" — μεσότοιχον (Strong\'s G3320) is a hapax legomenon in the NT. HISTORICAL: This likely alludes to the soreg, the stone barrier in the Jerusalem temple beyond which no Gentile could pass on pain of death. Inscriptions warning Gentiles have been archaeologically recovered. TYPOLOGY: Christ\'s flesh, torn on the cross, corresponds to the temple veil torn at His death (Matt 27:51), removing the barrier between God and humanity and between Jew and Gentile.',
        15: 'GREEK: "καταργήσας" (katargēsas) — "having rendered inoperative" or "having abolished" — does not mean the moral law ceases to exist but that the law "of commandments in ordinances" (τὸν νόμον τῶν ἐντολῶν ἐν δόγμασιν) as a dividing barrier between Jew and Gentile has been nullified. THEOLOGICAL: The "one new man" (ἕνα καινὸν ἄνθρωπον) is neither Jew nor Gentile but a new humanity constituted in Christ — the new Adam and head of a new race (cf. 2 Cor 5:17; Gal 3:28).',
        18: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse is profoundly Trinitarian in structure: access is through the Son (δι\' αὐτοῦ), in one Spirit (ἐν ἑνὶ πνεύματι), to the Father (πρὸς τὸν πατέρα). GREEK: "προσαγωγήν" (prosagōgēn, Strong\'s G4318) — "access" or "introduction" — a term used for formal introduction into the presence of a king. Both groups ("οἱ ἀμφότεροι," hoi amphoteroi, "the both") share equal access to the divine throne.',
        20: 'TYPOLOGY: The temple imagery here echoes the Solomonic temple built upon a massive cornerstone (1 Kgs 5-6; Isa 28:16; Ps 118:22). Christ is the ἀκρογωνιαῖος (akrogōniaios) — the "chief cornerstone" (Strong\'s G204) — the stone that determines the alignment of the entire structure. THEOLOGICAL: The "foundation of the apostles and prophets" likely refers to New Testament apostles and prophets (cf. Eph 3:5; 4:11), as the foundation they laid through their testimony concerning Christ.',
        22: 'GREEK: "συνοικοδομεῖσθε" (synoikodomeisthe, Strong\'s G4925) — "are being built together" — present passive, indicating an ongoing divine construction project. THEOLOGICAL: The chapter concludes where it began — with the Gentile addressees ("you also") — but now they are no longer dead in sin (v.1) but being incorporated as living stones into God\'s dwelling place. "κατοικητήριον τοῦ θεοῦ ἐν πνεύματι" (katoikētērion tou theou en pneumati) — "a dwelling place of God in the Spirit" — the church as the new temple replaces the Jerusalem temple as the locus of God\'s presence among His people (cf. 1 Cor 3:16; 1 Pet 2:5).',
    },
    3: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Désmios" (δέσμιος, Strong\'s G1198) means "prisoner" or "one bound in chains." Paul writes from imprisonment, likely in Rome (ca. AD 60-62). The sentence breaks off (anacolouthon) and resumes at v.14, indicating the parenthetical nature of vv.2-13. HISTORICAL: Paul\'s self-designation as "the prisoner of Christ Jesus" reframes Roman captivity as divine service—his chains belong to Christ, not Caesar.',
        3: 'GREEK: "Apokálypsis" (ἀποκάλυψις, G602) denotes an unveiling or disclosure of what was previously hidden. "Mystḗrion" (μυστήριον, G3466) is not a puzzle to be solved but a divine plan now revealed. THEOLOGICAL: Paul claims direct revelatory knowledge, not human tradition, as the source of his gospel—paralleling his testimony in Galatians 1:11-12.',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: The mystery was not absolutely unknown in the OT but was not made known "as" (hōs) it has now been revealed—indicating a fuller, clearer disclosure in the apostolic era. The Spirit is the agent of this revelation. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The "sons of men" (tois huiois tōn anthrōpōn) contrasts the human realm with the divine council where God\'s purposes originate; what was veiled from the earthly realm is now openly declared.',
        6: 'GREEK: Three compound "syn-" (σύν) words appear here—"synklēronóma" (fellow-heirs), "sýssōma" (of the same body), and "symmétocha" (fellow-partakers)—all emphasizing the full incorporation of Gentiles. "Sýssōma" (G4954) is a Pauline hapax legomenon, likely coined by Paul to express the unprecedented union of Jew and Gentile in one body. TYPOLOGY: The "promise" (epangelía) traces back to the Abrahamic covenant (Gen 12:3; Gal 3:8, 14, 29), now fulfilled in Christ.',
        8: 'GREEK: "Elachistotérō" (ἐλαχιστοτέρῳ) is a double comparative—a comparative form built on an already superlative word (eláchistos, "least"), yielding something like "less than the least." This is grammatically irregular and likely intentional Pauline coinage expressing profound humility. "Anexichníastos" (ἀνεξιχνίαστον, G421) means "untraceable, unsearchable," used also of God\'s ways in Romans 11:33.',
        10: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: "Archaîs" (ἀρχαῖς, G746) and "exousíais" (ἐξουσίαις, G1849) refer to spiritual rulers and authorities in the heavenly places (epouránia)—members of the divine council and cosmic powers. The assembly (ekklēsía) becomes the instrument through which God displays his wisdom to these heavenly beings. THEOLOGICAL: "Polypoíkilos" (πολυποίκιλος, G4182) means "many-sided, exceedingly variegated"—a hapax legomenon in the NT. God\'s wisdom is not monochrome but multifaceted, demonstrated supremely in the union of Jew and Gentile.',
        15: 'GREEK: "Patriá" (πατριά, G3965) means "family, lineage, clan" and derives from "patḗr" (father). Paul draws a deliberate wordplay: every "fathered-group" (patriá) derives its name and nature from the Father (patḗr). DIVINE_COUNCIL: "Every family in the heavens and upon earth" encompasses both angelic families (heavenly beings, divine council members) and human families—all deriving their identity from the one Father, affirming God\'s supreme headship over all realms of existence.',
        19: 'THEOLOGICAL: The love of Christ "surpassing knowledge" (hyperballousan tēs gnōseōs) indicates that experiential communion with Christ exceeds intellectual comprehension. "Plḗrōma toû theoû" (fullness of God) is among the most exalted phrases in Scripture—believers are to be filled unto the complete measure of divine fullness (cf. Col 1:19; 2:9-10). TYPOLOGY: The temple imagery of being "filled" echoes the glory of God filling the tabernacle (Exod 40:34) and temple (1 Kgs 8:11); the community of believers now becomes God\'s dwelling.',
        20: 'GREEK: "Hyperekperissou" (ὑπερεκπερισσοῦ, G5228+G1537+G4053) is a triple-compounded adverb meaning "far beyond all measure, superabundantly beyond." This extreme intensification is characteristically Pauline (cf. 1 Thess 3:10; 5:13). STRUCTURE: Verses 20-21 form a doxology closing the first half of Ephesians, marking the transition from doctrinal exposition (chs. 1-3) to practical exhortation (chs. 4-6).',
        21: 'THEOLOGICAL: Glory is ascribed both "in the assembly" and "in Christ Jesus"—the two are inseparable as the locus of God\'s self-glorification. "Unto all the generations of the age of the ages" (eis pásas tàs geneàs toû aiōnos tōn aiōnōn) is a uniquely expansive temporal expression, combining "generations" with the standard "age of ages" formula to convey unending, inexhaustible praise. STRUCTURE: This doxology forms the theological climax and structural hinge of the entire epistle.',
    },
    4: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Parakalō" (Strong\'s G3870) carries the sense of both exhortation and comfort — here it functions as an apostolic appeal. "Desmios" (G1198), prisoner/one in bonds, reflects Paul\'s literal imprisonment, yet he qualifies it "en kyriō" (in the Lord), reframing his captivity as service to Christ rather than to Rome. HISTORICAL: Paul writes from prison, likely in Rome (c. AD 60–62), making this appeal carry the weight of one who embodies the suffering he calls others to endure.',
        3: 'GREEK: "Spoudazontes" (G4704) implies urgent, zealous effort — not passive maintenance but active diligence. "Syndesmos" (G4886), bond or ligament, portrays peace as the binding sinew that holds unity intact. THEOLOGICAL: The unity is not one believers create but one the Spirit has already established; believers are called to preserve what God has accomplished.',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: The sevenfold list of "ones" in vv.4–6 (one body, one Spirit, one hope, one Lord, one faith, one baptism, one God and Father) forms a creedal confession structuring Trinitarian theology — the Spirit (v.4), the Lord Christ (v.5), and God the Father (v.6). This is among the earliest Trinitarian patterns in the New Testament.',
        8: 'TYPOLOGY: Paul quotes Psalm 68:18 (LXX 67:19), a victory psalm celebrating God\'s triumphal ascent of Mount Zion after conquering enemies. Paul applies this to Christ\'s ascension, recasting the divine warrior motif: Christ ascends to the heavenly throne and distributes gifts (the Spirit and gifted persons) to his people. The shift from "received gifts" (Hebrew/LXX) to "gave gifts" reflects an interpretive tradition also attested in the Targum on Psalms. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The imagery of ascending on high and leading captivity captive evokes the divine warrior\'s triumph over hostile spiritual powers (cf. Col 2:15).',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The lower parts of the earth" (ta katōtera merē tēs gēs) is debated — it may refer to the incarnation (descent to earth from heaven), to Hades/the realm of the dead, or to the grave. In light of the divine council framework, Christ\'s descent and ascent represent his complete sovereignty over every realm of the cosmos — heavenly, earthly, and subterranean (cf. Phil 2:9–10).',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: The one who descended is the very same one who ascended "hyperanō pantōn tōn ouranōn" — far above all the heavens. "Plērōsē ta panta" (that he might fill all things) declares Christ\'s cosmic lordship. He pervades and governs every sphere of creation. DIVINE_COUNCIL: Christ\'s ascent above all heavens places him above every rank of spiritual being in the heavenly hierarchy (cf. Eph 1:20–21).',
        11: 'GREEK: "Euangelistas" (G2099) appears only three times in the NT (here, Acts 21:8, 2 Tim 4:5) — one who announces the good news. "Poimen" (G4166), shepherd/pastor, is used here uniquely in the NT as a church office title. The single article governing "tous de poimenas kai didaskalous" suggests shepherds and teachers form a single functional category. STRUCTURE: The fivefold gifting (apostles, prophets, evangelists, shepherds-teachers) serves the threefold purpose stated in v.12.',
        13: 'GREEK: "Epignōsis" (G1922) denotes full, experiential knowledge — not merely intellectual assent but deep relational knowing of the Son of God. "Andra teleion" (mature man) uses "anēr" (adult male) rather than "anthrōpos," emphasizing full maturity. "Plērōma tou Christou" (fullness of Christ) echoes the cosmic fullness language of Eph 1:23. THEOLOGICAL: Corporate maturity, not merely individual growth, is in view — the entire body attaining to the full stature of Christ.',
        14: 'GREEK: "Klydōnizomenoi" (G2831) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning to be tossed by waves — vivid maritime imagery for doctrinal instability. "Kybeia" (G2940), also a NT hapax, literally means "dice-playing," hence trickery or sleight. "Methodeia" (G3180) appears only here and in Eph 6:11, denoting crafty scheming — in 6:11 it is attributed to the devil, suggesting that doctrinal deception has a demonic dimension.',
        18: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Pōrōsis tēs kardias" (hardening of the heart) echoes the OT motif of Israel\'s hardened heart (Isa 6:10; Mark 3:5). Here it is applied to Gentiles, whose spiritual condition apart from God mirrors rebellious Israel. The causal chain is significant: hardening leads to ignorance, ignorance leads to alienation from God\'s life, and alienation produces darkened understanding.',
        24: 'TYPOLOGY: The "new man created according to God" (ton kainon anthrōpon ton kata theon ktisthenta) echoes Genesis 1:26–27 — humanity made in God\'s image. The putting on of the new man is a new-creation motif: what was lost in Adam is restored in Christ (cf. Col 3:10; 2 Cor 5:17). "Dikaiosynē kai hosiotēti tēs alētheias" (righteousness and holiness of the truth) describes the moral character of this new creation.',
        25: 'TYPOLOGY: "Speak truth each one with his neighbor" quotes Zechariah 8:16 (LXX), connecting the ethics of the new community to the prophetic vision of restored Israel. The rationale — "for we are members of one another" — grounds ethical behavior in the one-body theology of vv.4 and 16.',
        26: 'GREEK: "Orgizesthe kai mē hamartanete" quotes Psalm 4:4 (LXX), a command acknowledging that anger itself is not necessarily sinful, but must be governed. "Parorgismos" (G3950) is a NT hapax legomenon denoting a provocation to wrath — distinct from "orgē" (settled anger). The sunset deadline reflects Jewish reckoning of the day ending at sundown, urging same-day reconciliation.',
        30: 'THEOLOGICAL: "To pneuma to hagion tou theou" (the Holy Spirit of God) is given full titular weight. "Esphragisthēte" (you were sealed) points back to Eph 1:13 — the Spirit is God\'s ownership seal and guarantee. Grieving the Spirit is possible precisely because he is personal, not an impersonal force. "Hēmeran apolytrōseōs" (day of redemption) refers to the eschatological consummation — the final deliverance of body and soul at Christ\'s return.',
        32: 'GREEK: "Chrēstoi" (G5543), kind or good, puns on "Christos" in early Christian tradition — believers are to be "Christ-like" in kindness. "Eusplanchnoi" (G2155), tenderhearted, literally means "having good intestines," as the ancients located compassion in the bowels. THEOLOGICAL: The ground of forgiveness is not human merit but divine action: "kathōs kai ho theos en Christō echarisato hymin" — even as God in Christ forgave you. Grace received becomes grace extended.',
    },
    5: {
        1: 'GREEK: μιμηταί (mimētai, Strong\'s G3402) means "imitators" — used by Paul also in 1 Cor 11:1 and 1 Thess 1:6. The term evokes active, deliberate copying of a model, not passive admiration. The grounding phrase "as beloved children" (ὡς τέκνα ἀγαπητά) establishes the familial identity that makes imitation possible: one imitates a Father to whom one truly belongs.',
        2: 'TYPOLOGY: The language of "offering and sacrifice" (προσφοράν καὶ θυσίαν) and "fragrance of sweet aroma" (ὀσμὴν εὐωδίας) deliberately echoes Levitical sacrifice language (Lev 1:9, 13, 17 LXX). Christ\'s self-giving fulfills and surpasses the entire sacrificial system. The phrase ὀσμὴν εὐωδίας appears repeatedly in the LXX for offerings acceptable to God, identifying Christ\'s death as the ultimate pleasing sacrifice.',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "the kingdom of Christ and of God" (τῇ βασιλείᾳ τοῦ Χριστοῦ καὶ θεοῦ) is remarkable — the single article τῇ governing both Χριστοῦ and θεοῦ under Granville Sharp\'s rule may indicate a shared divine identity between Christ and God. The covetous person is identified as an εἰδωλολάτρης (idolater, G1496), equating the worship of material gain with the worship of false gods — a theme rooted in the first commandment (Exod 20:3).',
        6: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: "Sons of disobedience" (τοὺς υἱοὺς τῆς ἀπειθείας) is a Hebraic idiom identifying those characterized by and belonging to the realm of disobedience — those under the dominion of the hostile spiritual powers mentioned in Eph 2:2. The "wrath of God" coming upon them reflects the divine judgment that falls on both the rebellious human and spiritual realms aligned against God\'s rule.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: The contrast is not merely moral but ontological: "you were darkness" (ἦτε σκότος), not merely "in darkness." Believers have undergone a transfer of identity and realm — from the domain of darkness to "light in the Lord" (φῶς ἐν κυρίῳ). This echoes Col 1:13 and the cosmic conflict framework of Ephesians (Eph 6:12). The imperative "walk as children of light" flows from the indicative of new identity.',
        14: 'TYPOLOGY: The quoted saying "Awake, O sleeper, and arise from the dead, and Christ shall shine upon you" does not match any single OT text exactly. It likely draws on Isa 26:19 and Isa 60:1 LXX, combining resurrection imagery with the dawn of divine glory. The verb ἐπιφαύσει (G2017, "shall shine upon") is a hapax legomenon in the NT, possibly adapted from the LXX of Isa 60:1 (φωτίζου). Early church tradition may have used this as a baptismal hymn fragment.',
        18: 'GREEK: μεθύσκεσθε (methyskesthe, G3182) is present passive imperative — "do not go on being made drunk." The contrast with πληροῦσθε ἐν πνεύματι (be filled in/by the Spirit) is striking: where wine leads to ἀσωτία (asōtia, G810, "dissipation/reckless abandon" — same word used of the prodigal son in Luke 15:13), the Spirit produces ordered worship described in vv. 19-21. HISTORICAL: Dionysiac worship involving wine-induced ecstasy was well known in Ephesus, making this contrast culturally pointed.',
        21: 'STRUCTURE: This participle ὑποτασσόμενοι ("submitting yourselves") is grammatically dependent on the imperative πληροῦσθε ("be filled") in v. 18, making mutual submission a fruit of Spirit-filling rather than an independent command. It also serves as a transitional hinge verse introducing the household code of 5:22–6:9. The phrase "in the fear of Christ" (ἐν φόβῳ Χριστοῦ) places Christ in the position of reverent awe normally reserved for God alone.',
        23: 'THEOLOGICAL: κεφαλή (kephalē, G2776, "head") is used in a dual analogy: husband-wife and Christ-assembly. Paul specifies that Christ\'s headship is exercised as σωτὴρ τοῦ σώματος ("savior of the body"), defining the nature of this headship as salvific self-sacrifice rather than mere authority. This redefines all human headship in light of Christ\'s pattern of costly, life-giving love.',
        26: 'TYPOLOGY: "The washing of the water in the word" (τῷ λουτρῷ τοῦ ὕδατος ἐν ῥήματι) draws on priestly purification rites (Exod 29:4; Lev 8:6) and Ezekiel\'s promise of cleansing water (Ezek 36:25). Christ acts as both the priest who purifies and the bridegroom who prepares his bride. The ῥῆμα (rhēma, G4487, "spoken word") likely refers to the gospel proclamation or baptismal confession accompanying the washing.',
        31: 'TYPOLOGY: This is a direct quotation of Gen 2:24 LXX. Paul reads the creation ordinance of marriage typologically as always having pointed toward the union of Christ and the assembly. The "leaving" and "joining" pattern foreshadowed from Eden the mystery of Christ leaving his heavenly Father to be united with his people — the true "one flesh" reality toward which human marriage points (v. 32).',
        32: 'GREEK: μυστήριον (mystērion, G3466) in Pauline usage does not mean "puzzle" but a divine plan once hidden and now revealed (Eph 1:9; 3:3-6; Col 1:26-27). Paul declares that the Gen 2:24 "one flesh" union was always, at its deepest level, about Christ and the assembly. This is the hermeneutical key to the entire passage: human marriage is an icon of the Christ-assembly union, not the reverse.',
    },
    6: {
        2: 'GREEK: Paul quotes the fifth commandment from Exodus 20:12 / Deuteronomy 5:16 (LXX). The phrase "first commandment with a promise" (entolē prōtē en epangelía) has been debated—it likely means first in prominence among those carrying an explicit blessing, not strictly first in numerical order. TYPOLOGY: The commandment bridges the Decalogue into the new covenant household, showing that Torah\'s moral imperatives remain operative in Christ.',
        4: 'GREEK: Paroргízō (G3949) means "to provoke to anger," a strong term for exasperating. Paideía (G3809) denotes training or discipline, and nouthesía (G3559) denotes admonition or corrective instruction—together they form a comprehensive model of formative and corrective upbringing. THEOLOGICAL: The qualifier "of the Lord" (kyríou) makes Christ the standard and authority behind all parental instruction.',
        5: 'HISTORICAL: Doûloi (G1401) refers to bondservants or slaves, reflecting the Roman household structure where enslaved persons served under a master (kyrios). Paul does not here endorse the institution but transforms the ethical framework within it—service rendered "as unto Christ" dignifies the servant and relativizes the master\'s authority. GREEK: Haplotēs (G572) connotes singleness of heart, undivided sincerity rather than duplicity.',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: Paul strikingly commands masters to "do the same things" (ta auta poieite) toward their bondservants—reciprocity that subverts the Roman social order. The grounding clause—that their Lord and the servants\' Lord is one and the same in the heavens—demolishes any basis for partiality. GREEK: Prosōpolēmpsia (G4382) means "respect of persons" or partiality based on external status, a term also used in Romans 2:11 and Colossians 3:25.',
        11: 'GREEK: Panoplía (G3833) denotes the complete suit of armor of a heavy infantryman—every piece, not merely selected parts. Methodeía (G3180) means crafty scheming or strategic deception, used only here and in Ephesians 4:14 in the NT. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The diábolos (G1228, "the slanderer/accuser") stands as the chief adversary whose stratagems are systematic—believers require divine equipment, not human resources, to withstand his cosmic opposition.',
        12: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: This verse catalogs the hostile spiritual hierarchy: archaí (rulers), exousíai (authorities), kosmokrátores (world-rulers) of this present darkness, and pneumatiká tēs ponērías (spiritual forces of wickedness) in the epouránia (heavenly places). These are the rebellious divine council members and their subordinates who exercise illegitimate dominion over the nations (cf. Deut 32:8 LXX; Dan 10:13, 20; Ps 82). GREEK: Kosmokrátōr (G2888) is a hapax legomenon in the NT, attested in astrological and magical texts for powerful cosmic spirits—Paul co-opts the term to identify demonic powers ruling this age\'s darkness. THEOLOGICAL: The battlefield is explicitly not against human beings (blood and flesh) but against a structured spiritual hierarchy, underscoring that the church\'s true warfare is transcendent.',
        13: 'THEOLOGICAL: The "evil day" (hēmera ponēra) likely refers not to a single eschatological moment alone but to any season of intensified spiritual assault. "Having accomplished all things" (hapanta katergasamenoi) indicates that standing firm requires active engagement—every duty fulfilled—before one can hold the ground. TYPOLOGY: The divine warrior motif echoes Isaiah 59:17 where the Lord himself dons armor; believers now wear the armor that God provides, participating in his own warfare against evil.',
        17: 'GREEK: Perikephalaía (G4030) is "helmet," and sōtērion (G4992) means "salvation" as a neuter substantive—echoing Isaiah 59:17 LXX where God puts on the helmet of salvation. Máchaira (G3162) denotes a short sword, and here it is identified as the rhēma theoû—the spoken word of God, distinct from lógos in emphasizing the utterance or declaration. TYPOLOGY: Christ himself wields the sword of his mouth (Rev 19:15); believers participate in the same divine weaponry through Spirit-empowered proclamation of God\'s word.',
        19: 'GREEK: Ánoixis (G457) is a hapax legomenon in the NT, meaning "opening"—Paul requests not merely courage but divinely granted speech itself, that his mouth would be opened with the right words. Mystḗrion (G3466) here refers to the revealed secret of Jew and Gentile united in one body through Christ (cf. Eph 3:3-6). THEOLOGICAL: Even the apostle depends on the prayers of the saints for effective proclamation—apostolic authority does not bypass the need for the Spirit\'s empowering through intercession.',
        20: 'HISTORICAL: Presbeúō (G4243) means "to serve as an ambassador"—a political term for an official representative of a sovereign. The irony is profound: Paul is an ambassador of the King of all kings, yet he serves en halýsei ("in a chain"), likely referring to his Roman custody. This juxtaposition highlights the paradox of the kingdom of Christ advancing through apparent weakness and suffering.',
        24: 'GREEK: Aphtharsía (G861) means "incorruptibility" or "imperishability"—the final word of the epistle qualifies the love believers have for the Lord Jesus Christ as undying, unfading, and beyond decay. Some take en aphtharsía with "grace" rather than "love," but the position strongly favors modifying the love of those who love Christ. THEOLOGICAL: The letter that began with every spiritual blessing in the heavenly places (1:3) closes with a benediction of grace upon an imperishable love—framing the entire epistle in the eternal, incorruptible purposes of God in Christ.',
    },
}